│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion failure inside                           │
│ DataLayout::getTypeSizeInBits which requires the queried type to be sized     │
│ (Ty->isSized()). An unsized type (specifically 'void') is being passed. In    │
│ LLVM IR, instructions like 'store' have result type 'void'. The SLP           │
│ vectorizer logic during computeMinimumValueSizes iterates over users of       │
│ certain scalar values and unconditionally queries the size of each user's     │
│ type. When a user is a 'store' instruction (void-typed), the call             │
│ DL->getTypeSizeInBits(U->getType()) triggers the assertion.                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows we are analyzing a store chain of length 2 and building a │
│ vectorization tree. The crash happens after collecting internal users and     │
│ during computeMinimumValueSizes. The backtrace pinpoints line 16067 inside a  │
│ lambda passed to none_of(V->users(), ...). That lambda ends with 'return      │
│ DL->getTypeSizeInBits(U->getType()) > UserTESz;'. For a store instruction     │
│ user, U->getType() is void -> unsized -> assertion.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The code assumes that all users of the scalar values in this demotion         │
│ analysis produce values with sized types. However, IR users include           │
│ Instructions with void type (store, call returning void, etc.). The predicate │
│ inside none_of is intended to detect whether a user requires keeping a larger │
│ bit width. For void-typed instructions there is no meaningful result size;    │
│ they should not block demotion and must be skipped or treated as              │
│ non-problematic. Failing to guard leads directly to querying an unsized type. │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 16060-16068 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp to  │
│ add a guard before calling getTypeSizeInBits on U->getType(). Specifically,   │
│ modify the final return statement inside the lambda to:                       │
│ Type *UTy = U->getType();                                                     │
│ if (!UTy->isSized())                                                          │
│   return false; // Void or other unsized types cannot constrain bitwidth.     │
│ return DL->getTypeSizeInBits(UTy) > UserTESz;                                 │
│ This preserves existing logic but safely skips unsized types (treating them   │
│ as not forcing a wider bit width). The choice of returning false aligns with  │
│ earlier conditions: a true result indicates a problematic user preventing     │
│ demotion; void users should not prevent demotion.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ Adding an isSized() check prevents asserting on void types and maintains      │
│ correct semantics of the demotion heuristic. The fix is local, low risk, and  │
│ addresses the root cause of the crash without altering broader vectorization  │
│ decisions. After patch, computeMinimumValueSizes will ignore void-typed users │
│ rather than crashing, allowing the pass to proceed normally.                  │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
