  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an
assertion failure inside DataLayout::getTypeSizeInBits which requires the queried
type to be sized (Ty->isSized()). An unsized type (specifically 'void') is being
passed. In LLVM IR, instructions like 'store' have result type 'void'. The SLP
vectorizer logic during computeMinimumValueSizes iterates over users of certain
scalar values and unconditionally queries the size of each user's type. When a
user is a 'store' instruction (void-typed), the call
DL->getTypeSizeInBits(U->getType()) triggers the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe debug log shows we are analyzing a store chain of length 2 and building
a vectorization tree. The crash happens after collecting internal users and
during computeMinimumValueSizes. The backtrace pinpoints line 16067 inside a
lambda passed to none_of(V->users(), ...). That lambda ends with 'return
DL->getTypeSizeInBits(U->getType()) > UserTESz;'. For a store instruction user,
U->getType() is void -> unsized -> assertion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe
code assumes that all users of the scalar values in this demotion analysis
produce values with sized types. However, IR users include Instructions with void
type (store, call returning void, etc.). The predicate inside none_of is intended
to detect whether a user requires keeping a larger bit width. For void-typed
instructions there is no meaningful result size; they should not block demotion
and must be skipped or treated as non-problematic. Failing to guard leads
directly to querying an unsized type.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines
16060-16068 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp to add a guard
before calling getTypeSizeInBits on U->getType(). Specifically, modify the final
return statement inside the lambda to:\nType *UTy = U->getType();\nif
(!UTy->isSized())\n  return false; // Void or other unsized types cannot
constrain bitwidth.\nreturn DL->getTypeSizeInBits(UTy) > UserTESz;\nThis
preserves existing logic but safely skips unsized types (treating them as not
forcing a wider bit width). The choice of returning false aligns with earlier
conditions: a true result indicates a problematic user preventing demotion; void
users should not prevent demotion.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nAdding an isSized() check
prevents asserting on void types and maintains correct semantics of the demotion
heuristic. The fix is local, low risk, and addresses the root cause of the crash
without altering broader vectorization decisions. After patch,
computeMinimumValueSizes will ignore void-typed users rather than crashing,
allowing the pass to proceed normally.\n",
